    "uses": "I can find some information on the medicinal uses of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa. Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is used in traditional medicine for its potential antiviral, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties. It is also believed to have antioxidant and wound-healing effects. The plant is used to treat various health conditions, including fever, respiratory issues, and skin infections. Further research is needed to confirm its efficacy and safety for human consumption.",
    "taxonomy": "Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is a species of fern in the family Polypodiaceae. It is a type of epiphytic plant, which means it grows on other plants, such as trees. The classification of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is further divided into its genus, species, and sometimes subspecies levels. The genus Ascogrammitis is a part of the larger Polypodiaceae family, which consists of over 1,000 species of ferns. Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is native to tropical regions of Central and South America.",
    "benefits": "Ascogrammitis anfractuosa, a type of fern, is a relatively understudied plant, and research on its health benefits is limited. However, some studies suggest that ferns, including Ascogrammitis anfractuosa, may possess antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. These properties could potentially contribute to various health benefits, such as reducing oxidative stress and inflammation in the body. Further research is needed to fully understand the potential health benefits of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional before using any plant-based remedies.",
    "parts": "Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is a species of fern found in tropical regions. The medicinal parts of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa have been traditionally used in folk medicine. However, there is limited scientific research on the specific medicinal properties of this plant. The traditional uses of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa include treatment of various health conditions, but more studies are needed to confirm its efficacy. Further research is required to determine the specific medicinal parts and their uses.",
    "intro": "Ascogrammitis anfractuosa, also known as the Anfractuous Grammatophyllon, is a species of fern native to the tropical forests of Central and South America. The plant has been traditionally used for its medicinal properties, including its ability to lower blood pressure, reduce inflammation, and alleviate symptoms of respiratory issues such as bronchitis and asthma. The bioactive constituents of Ascogrammitis anfractuosa include flavonoids, alkaloids, and terpenoids, which are responsible for its therapeutic effects. In traditional herbal medicine, Ascogrammitis anfractuosa is often used to make teas, infusions, and tinctures, which are used to treat a range of ailments, including fever, coughs, and digestive issues."
